\section{Ablation Studies}

We conduct five controlled experiments to isolate the effect of individual design choices on segmentation quality. Unless otherwise noted, all variants use \texttt{U-Net} with a ResNet-50 encoder, AdamW ($\text{lr}{=}10^{-4}$, weight decay $10^{-4}$), cosine annealing, batch size~8, and input resolution $512{\times}512$. Each ablation trains for 80 epochs, matching the main experiments. The default loss is $\mathcal{L}_{\text{CE}} + \mathcal{L}_{\text{Dice}}$ (equal weights); augmentation is disabled except where it is the factor under study. Metrics are computed on the validation set (213 images).

\subsection{Backbone Capacity}

Tab.~\ref{tab:ablation_backbone} compares ResNet-18 (${\sim}$14\,M params) and ResNet-50 (${\sim}$33\,M params) as the \texttt{U-Net} encoder. ResNet-50 outperforms ResNet-18 by 4.8\,pp in mIoU (0.163 vs.\ 0.115), confirming that additional depth and capacity translate to meaningful gains even on a dataset of only 209 images. The improvement in mDice (+7.4\,pp) is proportionally larger, indicating that ResNet-50 is better at segmenting rare foreground classes where the Dice metric is more sensitive. However, both backbones remain below the 80-epoch main-experiment results (mIoU 0.32), suggesting that the 25-epoch ablation budget is insufficient for full convergence.

