\subsection{Data Augmentation}

Tab.~\ref{tab:ablation_aug} compares training with and without geometric augmentation (random horizontal and vertical flips, $p{=}0.5$ each). Surprisingly, the no-augmentation variant achieves higher mIoU (0.193 vs.\ 0.144). Within the short 25-epoch budget, augmentation introduces additional input variability that slows convergence, and the model does not train long enough to benefit from the regularisation effect. This result suggests that augmentation gains are contingent on sufficient training duration; our main 80-epoch experiments, which do use augmentation, allow enough time for the regularisation benefit to materialise.

