\subsection{Loss Function}

Tab.~\ref{tab:ablation_loss} evaluates three loss configurations. Dice-only loss achieves the highest mIoU (0.287), substantially outperforming both cross-entropy only (0.142) and the combined CE+Dice (0.179). This confirms that Dice loss is better suited to the severe class imbalance of Pascal VOC: by directly optimising per-class overlap, it prevents the model from concentrating on the dominant background class. Cross-entropy, despite providing stable per-pixel gradients, is biased toward high-frequency classes and yields the lowest mIoU. The combined loss falls between the two, as the CE term partially dilutes the class-balancing effect of Dice. Note that the main experiments use equal-weight $\mathcal{L}_{\text{CE}} + \mathcal{L}_{\text{Dice}}$ rather than the 0.7+0.3 split tested here; the equal weighting was chosen based on preliminary experiments at the full 80-epoch budget.

